{"title_page": "Stay Up Late", "text_new": "{{About|the painting|the Talking Heads song|Little Creatures}}\n{{Infobox artwork\n| title              = Stay Up Late\n| image_file         = \n| artist             = Brian Swords\n| year               = 1992\n| medium             = [[Watercolor]]\n| movement           = [[Furry fandom]]\n| height_imperial    = 18\n| width_imperial     = 24\n| owner        = [[John Oliver]]\n}}\n'''''Stay Up Late''''' is a 1992 [[furry fandom]] [[Watercolor painting|watercolor]] painting by Brian Swords. It depicts two [[Anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] [[Rat|rats]] embracing. The painting gained prominence when [[John Oliver]] offered to buy the painting in the [[List of Last Week Tonight with John Oliver episodes#Season 7 (2020)|29 March 2020 episode]] of [[Last Week Tonight with John Oliver]].\n\n''Stay Up Late'' was created in 1992 by [[York, Pennsylvania|York]], [[Pennsylvania]] artist Brian Swords.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Whalen|first=Andrew|url=https://www.newsweek.com/last-week-tonight-john-oliver-rat-erotica-brian-swords-painting-furry-art-auction-1495063|title=The True Story Behind 'Last Week Tonight's' Rat Erotica Painting|date=30 March 2020|work=Newsweek|access-date=13 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was one of several of Swords's paintings, such as ''The Smell of Wet Fur'' and ''Sheets and Pillowcases'', that depict anthropomorphic rats, named Alice and Bob, in sexually suggestive poses.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Scolforo|first=Liz Evans|url=https://www.yorkdispatch.com/story/news/local/2020/03/30/last-week-tonight-host-seeks-rat-painting-york-artist-brian-swords/5087045002/|title=No joke: John Oliver wants Yorker's rat erotica, and he's willing to pay top dollar|date=30 March 2020|work=York Dispatch|access-date=13 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Between 1988 and 1993, Swords donated his paintings to \"Gallery 33\", [[WITF-TV]]'s yearly auction. His pieces sold well, but the donated paintings steadily became more explicit.<ref name=\":1\" /> Out of fear of alienating their audience and losing their FCC Licence, erotica was banned from the auction in 1993.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe painting depicts two [[Anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] [[Rat|rats]] in an embrace. Both of the rats are sitting on a large bed that is illuminated by candles. Behind them there is a large pump bottle of [[K-Y Jelly]] and a box of [[Facial tissue|facial tissues]] on top of the headboard.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n''Stay Up Late'' was sold for $80 to an unknown buyer in 1992.<ref name=\":0\" /> On 29 March 2020, [[John Oliver]] offered to buy the painting for $1000 and a $20,000 donation to a local [[food bank]] of the owner's choice.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Streva|first=Virginia|url=https://www.phillyvoice.com/john-oliver-rat-erotica-pennsylvania-york-covid-19-coronavirus-trump-last-week-tonight/|title=John Oliver desperately wants to buy rat-erotica painting by Pennsylvania artist|date=30 March 2020|work=Philly Voice|access-date=13 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Two weeks later, on 12 April 2020, Oliver was shown with the painting as part of his closing monologue of the episode.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Stairiker|first=Kevin|url=https://lancasteronline.com/features/john-oliver-of-hbos-last-week-tonight-receives-york-mans-furry-art/article_e814e5d6-7daa-11ea-b90c-7ba90d03605d.html|title=John Oliver of HBO's 'Last Week Tonight' receives York man's 'furry' art|date=13 April 2020|work=Lancaster Online|access-date=13 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The seller remains anonymous and Oliver did not mention which food bank received the donation, except that it was in Pennsylvania.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Argento|first=Mike|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2020/04/14/john-oliver-gives-world-hope-form-rat-erotica-pa-artist/2988706001/|title=John Oliver gives the world hope in the form of rat erotica painted by a Pa. artist|date=14 April 2020|work=York Daily Record|access-date=14 April 2020|url-status=live|publisher=USA Today}}</ref> \n\nThe point of Oliver's stunt was to show how much easier it is to buy a particular painting from an unknown artist than it is to get [[COVID-19 testing|tested for COVID-19]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Argento|first=Mike|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2020/03/30/john-oliver-looking-painting-york-artist/5085997002/|title=John Oliver wants York artist's painting, offering $1K and $20K donation to local food bank|date=30 March 2020|work=York Daily Record|access-date=14 April 2020|url-status=live|publisher=USA Today}}</ref> Emily Chambers, writing for politics blog Pajiba, referred to the extended joke as \"greatest story of the past century.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pajiba.com/last_week_tonight/last-week-tonight-gives-us-the-rat-erotica-hope-we-didnt-know-we-needed-.php|title=Prepare To Have Your T*ts Blown Off With Inspiration By 'Last Week Tonight'|last=Chambers|first=Emily|date=13 April 2020|website=Pajiba|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref> Virginia Streva, writing for Philly Voice, called the quest for the painting a \"comedic victory.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Streva|first=Virgina|url=https://www.phillyvoice.com/john-oliver-rat-erotica-painting-pennyslvania-york-artist-last-week-tonight-coronavirus-covid-19/|title=John Oliver obtains sought-after rat-erotica painting by Pennsylvania artist|date=13 April 2020|work=Philly Voice|access-date=14 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\n== Citations ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External Links==\n\n{{Last Week Tonight}}\n\n[[Category:1992 paintings]]\n[[Category:American paintings]]\n[[Category:Erotic art]]\n[[Category:Furry fandom]]\n[[Category:Last Week Tonight with John Oliver]]\n[[Category:Watercolor paintings]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the painting|the Talking Heads song|Little Creatures}}\n{{Infobox artwork\n| title              = Stay Up Late\n| image_file         = \n| artist             = Brian Swords\n| year               = 1992\n| medium             = [[Watercolor]]\n| movement           = [[Furry fandom]]\n| height_imperial    = 18\n| width_imperial     = 24\n| owner        = [[John Oliver]]\n}}\n'''''Stay Up Late''''' is a 1992 [[Furry fandom|fury fandom]] [[Watercolor painting|watercolor]] painting by Brian Swords. It depicts two [[Anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] [[Rat|rats]] embracing. The painting gained prominence when [[John Oliver]] offered to buy the painting in the [[List of Last Week Tonight with John Oliver episodes#Season 7 (2020)|29 March 2020 episode]] of [[Last Week Tonight with John Oliver]].\n\n''Stay Up Late'' was created in 1992 by [[York, Pennsylvania|York]], [[Pennsylvania]] artist Brian Swords.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Whalen|first=Andrew|url=https://www.newsweek.com/last-week-tonight-john-oliver-rat-erotica-brian-swords-painting-furry-art-auction-1495063|title=The True Story Behind 'Last Week Tonight's' Rat Erotica Painting|date=30 March 2020|work=Newsweek|access-date=13 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was one of several of Swords's paintings, such as ''The Smell of Wet Fur'' and ''Sheets and Pillowcases'', that depict anthropomorphic rats, named Alice and Bob, in sexually suggestive poses.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Scolforo|first=Liz Evans|url=https://www.yorkdispatch.com/story/news/local/2020/03/30/last-week-tonight-host-seeks-rat-painting-york-artist-brian-swords/5087045002/|title=No joke: John Oliver wants Yorker's rat erotica, and he's willing to pay top dollar|date=30 March 2020|work=York Dispatch|access-date=13 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Between 1988 and 1993, Swords donated his paintings to \"Gallery 33\", [[WITF-TV]]'s yearly auction. His pieces sold well, but the donated paintings steadily became more explicit.<ref name=\":1\" /> Out of fear of alienating their audience and losing their FCC Licence, erotica was banned from the auction in 1993.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe painting depicts two [[Anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] [[Rat|rats]] in an embrace. Both of the rats are sitting on a large bed that is illuminated by candles. Behind them there is a large pump bottle of [[K-Y Jelly]] and a box of [[Facial tissue|facial tissues]] on top of the headboard.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n''Stay Up Late'' was sold for $80 to an unknown buyer in 1992.<ref name=\":0\" /> On 29 March 2020, [[John Oliver]] offered to buy the painting for $1000 and a $20,000 donation to a local [[food bank]] of the owner's choice.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Streva|first=Virginia|url=https://www.phillyvoice.com/john-oliver-rat-erotica-pennsylvania-york-covid-19-coronavirus-trump-last-week-tonight/|title=John Oliver desperately wants to buy rat-erotica painting by Pennsylvania artist|date=30 March 2020|work=Philly Voice|access-date=13 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Two weeks later, on 12 April 2020, Oliver was shown with the painting as part of his closing monologue of the episode.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Stairiker|first=Kevin|url=https://lancasteronline.com/features/john-oliver-of-hbos-last-week-tonight-receives-york-mans-furry-art/article_e814e5d6-7daa-11ea-b90c-7ba90d03605d.html|title=John Oliver of HBO's 'Last Week Tonight' receives York man's 'furry' art|date=13 April 2020|work=Lancaster Online|access-date=13 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The seller remains anonymous and Oliver did not mention which food bank received the donation, except that it was in Pennsylvania.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Argento|first=Mike|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2020/04/14/john-oliver-gives-world-hope-form-rat-erotica-pa-artist/2988706001/|title=John Oliver gives the world hope in the form of rat erotica painted by a Pa. artist|date=14 April 2020|work=York Daily Record|access-date=14 April 2020|url-status=live|publisher=USA Today}}</ref> \n\nThe point of Oliver's stunt was to show how much easier it is to buy a particular painting from an unknown artist than it is to get [[COVID-19 testing|tested for COVID-19]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Argento|first=Mike|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2020/03/30/john-oliver-looking-painting-york-artist/5085997002/|title=John Oliver wants York artist's painting, offering $1K and $20K donation to local food bank|date=30 March 2020|work=York Daily Record|access-date=14 April 2020|url-status=live|publisher=USA Today}}</ref> Emily Chambers, writing for politics blog Pajiba, referred to the extended joke as \"greatest story of the past century.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pajiba.com/last_week_tonight/last-week-tonight-gives-us-the-rat-erotica-hope-we-didnt-know-we-needed-.php|title=Prepare To Have Your T*ts Blown Off With Inspiration By 'Last Week Tonight'|last=Chambers|first=Emily|date=13 April 2020|website=Pajiba|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref> Virginia Streva, writing for Philly Voice, called the quest for the painting a \"comedic victory.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Streva|first=Virgina|url=https://www.phillyvoice.com/john-oliver-rat-erotica-painting-pennyslvania-york-artist-last-week-tonight-coronavirus-covid-19/|title=John Oliver obtains sought-after rat-erotica painting by Pennsylvania artist|date=13 April 2020|work=Philly Voice|access-date=14 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\n== Citations ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External Links==\n\n{{Last Week Tonight}}\n\n[[Category:1992 paintings]]\n[[Category:American paintings]]\n[[Category:Erotic art]]\n[[Category:Furry fandom]]\n[[Category:Last Week Tonight with John Oliver]]\n[[Category:Watercolor paintings]]\n", "name_user": "1857a", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stay_Up_Late"}
{"title_page": "J.H. Soeder", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox writer \n|name = J.H. Soeder\n|image =\n|birth_place = [[Phoenix, Arizona]], United States\n|genre = [[Author]] [[Muralist]]\n|nationality = [[United States|American]]\n|period = 1978\u2013present\n|notableworks = ''Haddie's in Our Closet'', ''The Element 238 Series''\n|awards = Foreword Reviews Book of the Year, The National Indie Excellence Book Awards,\n|website ={{URL|http://www.jhsoeder.com}}}}\n\n'''J.H. Soeder''' (born 1951) is an American artist and author. He was born in [[Phoenix, Arizona]], United States.\n\nSoeder's first non-fiction book, \u201cTrue Tails\u201d received two national book awards.  He then went on to write two other non-fiction books, \u201cFingers in the Light\u201d and \u201cHaddie\u2019s In Our Closet.\u201d He was also listed by the Organic View\u2019s Radio Show as having written one of the best books of 2011. \u201cHaddie\u2019s In Our Closet\u201d, an autobiographical ghost story, was a finalist in Foreword Reviews 2012 Book of the Year awards.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=https://botya.forewordreviews.com/finalists/2011/body-mind-and-spirit/ |title=2011 Finalists in Body, Mind & Spirit (Adult Nonfiction) \u2013 IndieFab Awards |publisher=Botya.forewordreviews.com |date= |accessdate=2015-02-22}}</ref> In 1976 Soeder ran in the Liberty Torch Race, now the [[World Harmony Run]], a 24-hour-a-day, nonstop, relay covering all 50 states to mark the [[United States Bicentennial]].<ref>[http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:LibertyTorchRunArticle.pdf ]{{dead link|date=October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Miami public art==\nIn 1977 Jon Soeder graduated from [[University of Miami]] with a Fine Arts and Bachelor of Science degree. Soeder's mural work can be seen all over the University of Miami. To commemorate the 50th anniversary of University of Miami, Soeder created a three part mural. Soeder's first work was on the patio of the Student Union. Soeder was then asked to design the walls of the entrance to the pool. In addition, Saga Foods had Soder paint the major cafeterias on campus with colorful designs, native flowers, and landscapes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://merrick.library.miami.edu/cdm/singleitem/collection/umphotos/id/2314/rec/44 |title=Mural outside of the Student Union :: UM Historical Photographs - Buildings and Grounds |publisher=Merrick.library.miami.edu |date=2008-01-23 |accessdate=2015-02-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.e-yearbook.com/yearbooks/University_Miami_Ibis_Yearbook/1978/Page_176.html |title=University of Miami - Ibis Yearbook (Coral Gables, FL), Class of 1978, Page 176 |publisher=E-yearbook.com |date= |accessdate=2015-02-22}}</ref>\n\nSoeder later installed graphics and murals all around Miami's [[Coconut Grove]]  and South Miami neighborhoods.\n\n==\"Element 238\" Series==\nSoeder is the author of the five part science fiction series, \u201cElement 238.\u201d The setting is Earth\u2019s future, three hundred and fifty years in the future, where ninety-eight percent of mankind has since been wiped out by a genetically created germ. Two scientists work together to discover what happened and what can be done to save the Earth. Four books have been published so far. According to the author's webpage, the fifth book is forthcoming.\n\n==Animal communication==\nSoeder claims to be able to communicate with animals. His autobiographical book, True Tails,  centers around his life with animals. He also works for the preservation of marine mammals\u2014his arguments for ending the killing of whales are expressed in his website, The Whale People. Although there is disagreement to whether [[animal communication]] is possible, Soeder has been sought after to speak about his experiences. He has been interviewed for his knowledge of animal communication.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blogtalkradio.com/theorganicview/2011/03/14/jon-soeder-true-tailsthe-real-story-about-real-animal-communicatio |title=The Organic View Online Radio |publisher=BlogTalkRadio |date= |accessdate=2015-02-22}}</ref>\n\n==Book awards==\n''Haddie\u2019s In Our Closet!''\n*2011 The Organic View\u2019s Best Books of 2011<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theorganicview.com/wiki/index.php?title=December,_2011#Author.2C_J.H._Soeder_.26_June_Stoyer:_The_Best_Books_of_2011_-_Dec_28.2C2011 |title=December, 2011 |publisher=The Organic View |date= |accessdate=2015-02-22}}</ref>\n*2011 Foreword\u2019s Book of the Year Awards (Finalist)<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n''True Tails''\n*2010 The National Indie Excellence Book Awards (Winner)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indieexcellence.com/indie-results-2010.php |title=Indie Excellence\u00ae Awards 2010 Book Award Winners |publisher=Indieexcellence.com |accessdate=2015-02-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226024239/http://www.indieexcellence.com/indie-results-2010.php |archivedate=2015-02-26 }}</ref>\n*2010 [[Hollywood Book Festival]] Awards (Runner Up)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodbookfestival.com/winners2010.htm |title=Hollywood Book Festival |publisher=Hollywood Book Festival |date=2010-07-12 |accessdate=2015-02-22}}</ref>\n\n''The Way of the Eagle: An Early California Journey of Awakening (illustrator)''\n*2012 The Next Generation Indie Book Awards (Finalist)<ref>[http://www.indiebookawards.com*/2012_winners_and_finalists.php] {{dead link|date=February 2015}}</ref>\n*2011 USA Best Book Awards (Finalist)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usabooknews.com/images/2011_best_book_award_results.pdf |title=The 2011 USA Best Book Awards |publisher=Usbooknews.com |accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n*Close Encounters of the Creature Kind\n*Element 238 - The Search for Truth - Episode 1\n*Element 238 - The Deathly Fall - Episode 2\n*Element 238 - The Flight for Survival - Episode 3\n*Element 238 - The Hidden Enemy - Episode 4\n*Fingers in the Light\n*The Frogs and the Paper Wasps\n*Haddie's in Our Closet!\n*The Squirrel and the Golf Ball\n*Stroker\n*The Tegu\n*True Tails\n*The Way of the Eagle: An Early California Journey of Awakening (illustrator)\n\n==Partial list of reviews==\n*Flaming Net<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://www.flamingnet.com/bookreviews/newreviews/newbookreview.cfm?title=True%20Tails |title=Flamingnet New Book Review |publisher=Flamingnet.com |date=2007-05-31 |accessdate=2015-02-22}}</ref>\n*Flaming Net<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n*Reader Views<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readerviews.com/ReviewSoederTrueTails.html |accessdate=January 22, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110209123739/http://www.readerviews.com/ReviewSoederTrueTails.html |archivedate=February 9, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Selected radio interviews==\n*Author, Jon Soeder: Fingers In The Light<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.theorganicview.com/health/author-jon-soeder-fingers-in-the-light/ |title=Author, Jon Soeder: Fingers In The Light &#124; |publisher=Theorganicview.com |date=2011-08-01 |accessdate=2015-02-22}}</ref>\n*Author, J.H. Soeder: Haddie's in Our Closet!<ref>{{cite web|url=http://castroller.com/Podcasts/TheOrganicView/2664284 |title=The Organic View |publisher=CastRoller |date= |accessdate=2015-02-22}}</ref>\n*Author, J.H. Soeder & June Stoyer: The Best Books of 2011<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blogtalkradio.com/theorganicview/2011/12/28/author-jh-soeder-june-stoyer-the-best-books-of-2011 |title=Author, J.H. Soeder & June Stoyer: The Best Books of 2011 12/28 by The Organic View &#124; Environment Podcasts |publisher=Blogtalkradio.com |date=2011-12-28 |accessdate=2015-02-22}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.thewhalepeople.com The Whale People]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Soeder, J. H.}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:American artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Miami alumni]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=Augus