dition, Saga Foods had Soder paint the major cafeterias on campus with colorful designs, native flowers, and landscapes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://merrick.library.miami.edu/cdm/singleitem/collection/umphotos/id/2314/rec/44 |title=Mural outside of the Student Union :: UM Historical Photographs - Buildings and Grounds |publisher=Merrick.library.miami.edu |date=2008-01-23 |accessdate=2015-02-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.e-yearbook.com/yearbooks/University_Miami_Ibis_Yearbook/1978/Page_176.html |title=University of Miami - Ibis Yearbook (Coral Gables, FL), Class of 1978, Page 176 |publisher=E-yearbook.com |date= |accessdate=2015-02-22}}</ref>\n\nSoeder later installed graphics and murals all around Miami's [[Coconut Grove]]  and South Miami neighborhoods.\n\n==\"Element 238\" Series==\nSoeder is the author of the five part science fiction series, \u201cElement 238.\u201d The setting is Earth\u2019s future, three hundred and fifty years in the future, where ninety-eight percent of mankind has since been wiped out by a genetically created germ. Two scientists work together to discover what happened and what can be done to save the Earth. Four books have been published so far. According to the author's webpage, the fifth book is forthcoming.\n\n==Animal communication==\nSoeder claims to be able to communicate with animals. His autobiographical book, True Tails,  centers around his life with animals. He also works for the preservation of marine mammals\u2014his arguments for ending the killing of whales are expressed in his website, The Whale People. Although there is disagreement to whether [[animal communication]] is possible, Soeder has been sought after to speak about his experiences. He has been interviewed for his knowledge of animal communication.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blogtalkradio.com/theorganicview/2011/03/14/jon-soeder-true-tailsthe-real-story-about-real-animal-communicatio |title=The Organic View Online Radio |publisher=BlogTalkRadio |date= |